{"/service/ndnp/mdu/batch_mdu_jackinthepulpit_ver01/data/sn83016209/00383342260/1958010201/0006.xml":{"full_text":"COUNTY'S\nONLY ABC\nNEWSPAPER\nit\n102nd Year No. 5 Established 1855 by Matthew Fields ROCKVILLE, MARYLAND THURSDAY. JANUARY 2, 1958 Montgomery County's Oldest Newspaper Five Cents a Copy\nNew AEC Building\nWill Open Monday\n1625 Aides\nStart Move\nI\nTomorrow\nStep Brings\nsl2 Million\nPayroll Here\nf\nBy Steed Evans\nStaff Reporter\nTomorrow afternoon, be- i\ntween 18 and 20 brown and\nbeige vans will begin loading\ndesks and file cases for the:\nfirst of a two-stage moving;\noperation of the Atomic En\nergy Commission from the\nDistrict to the new headquar\nters in Germantown.\nWorkmen will begin clearing\nAEC offices on six floors at 1717\nH Street N. W. shortly after 700\nemployes quit work for the week\nend. They will report for work\nMonday or Tuesday in the brand\nnew building.\nThe second half of the gigantic\nmove, described by some as the\nlargest in history, will start late\nnext Friday for another 700 em\nployes and continue through the\nweek-end. That operation will\nclear the agency\u2019s offices at 1901\nConstitution Avenue N. W.\nOnly 225 employes wlil be left\nbehind pending completion of the\nlast wing of the new building.\nFewer Losses\nAEC officials once were afraid\nthey were going to lose almost a\nthird of the agency's 1625 em\nployes because of the move. But\nAEC Will Have\nBank Facility\nA check-cashing facility\nwill be opened by the Ger\nmantown Bank in the new\nAtomic Energy Commission\nBuilding on Tuesday, Janu\nary 7.\nIn announcing the new op\neration, A. R. Selby, president\nof the bank, indicated that fa\ncility would be gradually ex\npanded to include additional\nbanking services. The neW\noffice will not be open to the\npublic. Selby pointed out, but\nonly to employes of AEC.\na wholesale cut was averted, par\ntially by a sudden dip in Federal\nemployment in the District and\npartially because people have be\ncome accustomed to the idea of\nmoving.\nThe unemployment was caused\nby massive Defense Department\ncuts in force.' People found there\nweren\u2019t as many openings as\nwhen they first warned the AEC\nthey wouldn\u2019t make the move.\nTrips through the handsome\nnew building, dedicated by Presi\ndent Eisenhower, and the fact\nthat new roads from the District\nline to the AEC have been com\npleted also assuaged many work\ners.\nWhen they report for work in\nthe $13.3 million building, em\nployes will find parking room for\n800 cars and a view of rolling\ngreen hills from all of the mod\nem, swing-out windows. An au\nditorium also has been provided.\nThe employes will bring to the\narea a total annual payroll of\nsl2 million. The average salary,\nofficials said, is close to S7OOO per\nyear.\nAt least 125 families, one or\nmore members of which work\nfor the AEC, have moved north\nof the half-way line between the\nold locations and the new one.\nThe lines, a spokesman said, was\nnear the terminus of Old George\ntown Road and the Rockville Pike\njust south of Rockville.\nThe largest single group of\nworkers who won\u2019t make the\nmove are the unmarried, younger\nwomen who rent apartments in\nthe Metropolitan area.\nThe AEC will start a busline\nJanuary 6 to bring employes from\nihe far sections of the District\nand Virginia to the new building.\nOne route will start in Virginia\nand the other in D. C.\nJ\u2022\n3 1 rtpief Hiii| Sentinel\nDuring Historic Move\nArmed Guards to Watch\nOver Mass of AEC Data\nA bit of the old West will accompany the Atomic Energy\nCommission when it starts its move to Germantown tomor\nrow evening.\nArmed guards will \u201cride shot\ngun\u201d on Curies\u2019 moving vans,\nmany of which will be crammed\nwith classified documents. All will\nbe locked.\nApproximately 50 percent of\nthe AEC material to be moved\nis classified for security pur\nposes, a moving official said.\nThe AEC and the moving com\npany both will take unusual pre\ncautions with the cargo. Dis\npatchers for both will team side\nby side at the embarkation and\narrival points.\nFurther, the AEC has run se\ncurity checks on all of Curies\u2019 80\nto 100 employes who will take\npart in the safari. They will\nload, move and unload an es\ntimated 275 truckloads before the\njob is through.\nA spokesman for Curies said\nthat about 18 trucks will be shut\ntling between the old and new\nAEC buildings from this Friday\nuntil January 14. Workmen will\ntoil on two, 12-hour shifts.\nCuries won out over other bid\nders by contracting for the job\nat $40,000. Negotiations started\none month ago. Curles-already is\nCemetery\nLaw Laid\nTo Rest\nThe county\u2019s proposed cem\netery ordinance, although not\nyet pronounced dead, shows\nno sign of getting up off the\ntable where the County Coun\ncil placed it gingerly last Tues\nday.\nThe Council\u2019s action followed a\nturnout of aroused citizens who\nprotested against the ordinance\nDecember 10. Ten opposing let\nters have been received by the\nCouncil since then.\nCouncilman J. Grahame Walk\ner apparently spoke the mind of\nthe majority of his colleagues\nwhen he said. \u2019\u2019l'm not convinced\nthere is a problem.\u201d\nThe tabling motion was offered\nby Councilman Jerry T. Williams.\nThe Council then voted \u201caye\u201d\non a motion by Couneilwoman\nStella B. Werner to have Dr. W.\nJ. Peeples, County Health Direc\ntor, and Charles M. Irelan, County\nAttorney, to advise the council on\nits responsibilities toward ceme\nteries.\nThe original ordinance proposed\nthat all new cemeteries be\nlicensed and be at least 50 acres\nlarge. Fees would have to be paid,\ntrust funds set up, records kept.\nSome church officials argued the\nproposal might legislate them out\nof existence.\nAt Tuesday\u2019s short session,\nCouncilman Robert T. Snure was\nunsuccessful in persuading the\ncouncil to appoint a special com\nmittee of clergymen, health offi\ncials and morticians to study the\nneed for cemetery legislation and\nreport back June 1.\nAward Planned\nFor Policemen\nPlans to establish a \u201cPolice\nman of the Year\u201d award have\nbeen announced by County Man\nager Melvin L. Reese.\nSponsored by the Knights of\nColumbus, the award will be a\ngold medal to be known as the\n\u201cColumbian Medal of Merit.\u201d\nCandidates will be selected for\nheroism, and for courage, persist\nence and patience, leadeiVhlp,\ngood judgment, cndurance\\and\ninitiative.\n\njockeying for what it calls the\nnext biggest job in its history\u2014\nthe transplanting of the Veterans\nAdministration to Philadelphia in\nthe near future.\nOfficials for the General Serv\nices Administration, which con\ntracts for all Government trans\nportation, said that tfye AEC move\nis the biggest of its type in the\nhistory of the Washington area.\nThe trucks are expected to pro\nceed out Wisconsin Avenue to the\nDistrict line at Western Avenue\nand thence north along the Rock\nville Pike until they come to the\nMontrose cutoff. They will take\nMontrose Road to the newly\nopened Washington National Pike\nwhich passes within 300 yards of\nthe AEC.\nWashington and Montgomery\nCounty police departments have\nbeen asked to aid the heavily\nladen trucks in traffic. They will\nmove singly, rather than in cara\nvan.\nNo bridge or other road ob\nstructions will block the tractor\ntrailers along their route.\nIn Rockville\nBusiness\n\nOutlook\nBrightens\nRockville\u2019s rapidly-growing\nbusiness community is attract\ning large numbers of shoppers\nfrom the heavily-populated\nareas south of the city, a sur\nvey by this newspaper showed\nthis week.\nSanta Claus alone is not re\nsponsible it was learned in check\ning clothing, appliances, furniture,\nhardware, department and other\nstores.\nAlthough this Christmas shop\nping season set new records at\nmost of the stores, it Is the steady\nincrease from year to year that is\ndelighting the businessmen.\nWhat accounts for the in\ncrease?\n\u201cThe overall picture of the\nshopper being able to find what\nhe wants has improved in the\npast four years and so has our\nbusiness,\u201d says Mrs. Charles\nBurke, wife of the owner of Town\nand Country Electric.\n\"The more business here, the\nbetter for all of us,\u201d agrees Rob\nert C. Clearwater, vice president\nof Transcolor Photo on North\nWashington Street.\nThe improved highways, better\nparking, and less traffic conges\ntion, Clearwater says, are bring\ning him more and more custom\ners from Randolph Hills, Wheat\non, Kensington and the midcoun\nty areas.\nAs the word spreads and the\npeople in these areas realize how\nfast Rockville is growing, they\nwill turn away from Silver Spring\nand Bethesrla and drive to Rock\nville, Clearwater feels. \u201cStore\nowners who fear the opening of\nnew shopping centers here are\nmaking a mistake,\u201d he added.\nOne lone dissenter to the glow\n(Continued on Page 5)\nSeen Any Change\nIn Traffic Here?\nSix thousand cars a day art\nnow using the new Montrose\nRoad interchange, draining\noff 2500 cars a day from\nMontgomery Avenue in Rock\nville, Mason Butcher, director\nof public works, told the\nCounty Council Tuesday.\nA Century of Service to Montgomery County 2 SECTIONS 10 PAGES\nl PI j\nk Jfej \u25a0n\nPRESENTS FROM PINNEBERG brighten Rockville City Hall. City\nManager John Markland browses through the album of prints\ndepicting scenes of Pinneberg\u2019s life. The art work on the wall is\nthe handiwork of Pinneberg school children. The \u201ccowboys\u201d and\u2019\ncovered wagons represent German migration to the east in the\n13th century rather than the American western movement. The\ngifts were part of a Christmas package Pinneberg sent as a mes\nsage of good will to its Sister-City Rockville. Staff Photo by\nG os bee.\nWe Didn\u2019t Give\nGerman Yule Gift\nMakes Faces Red\n\nDid you suffer the embarrassment of getting an ex\ntremely thoughtful, nice gift from someone that you didn\u2019t\ndo anything at all for at Christmas?\nIt happened to the City of\nRockville.\nRed-faced officials this week\nannounced the receipt of an elab\norate gift, package from Rock\nville\u2019s Sister City, Pinneberg,\nGermany, five days before\nChristmas. Then they embar\nressedly confessed that Rockville;\nhadn\u2019t sent anything to the peo- i\npie of Pinneberg-\nAn extenuating fact was that!\npreparation of a Christmas pack-1\nAge to Pinneberg was started;\njust before Christmas. But it!\nstill hasn\u2019t been mailed.\nOfficials said the trouble was 1\nthat an official okay could noti\nbe obtained because the Sister\nCity advisory committee had\nbeen without a chairman since\nthe Rev. James Fahl resigned'\nlast month.\n1957 Was Eventful\nYear for County\nThe year 1957 was an eventful\none for growing Montgomery!\nCounty. Following is the cream j\nof the county news crop skimfned j\nfrom, the pages of this news-i\npaper:\nJanuary\nElementary school children get i\ntuberculin tests in a move awayi\nfrom mass X-ray diagnosis for\nstudents The Post Office De\npartment accepts a proposal to\nbuild a Twinbrook substation on j\nViers Mill Road School Su-j\nperintendent Forbes Norris pro-1\nposes a $33,404,472 school budget,j\npredicts a rise in enrollment to J\n62,633 pupils Lathrop E.\nI Write a Letter; Win Prize\nThe Sentinel has a problem it will pay S3O to soive.\nThis is it: shall we stop calling the old Rt. 240 by that name\nor should we use its new, correct name, Rt. 355?\nThis major road gets mentioned many times in this paper.\nIf we started calling it Rt. 355 many of our readers wouldn't\nknow what we were talking about.\nOn the other hand, if we continue calling it Old 240, the\nRockville Pike, the Frederick road, or any of several other\nnames, we will be technically inaccurate. As you know, the\nnumber 240 now designates the big, new Washington National\nTurnpike. y\nSo we came up with the idea of paying sls, $lO and $5\nto the authors of three letters we think best state the road for\nus to take.\nSign your name and we\u2019ll print your leter. Maybe you'll\nwin.\nRobert Bonham, Navy Depart\nment attorney, of TMnbrook,\nhad been nominated as head of\nthe committee but had not yet\naccepted.\nAwaiting official approval was\na tape recording, \u201cAn Evening of\nChristmas Music,\u201d by the Rich\nard Montgomery Senior Glee\nClub and the 10th grade chorus\nunder direction of John E.\nPreston.\nThe package will also contain\nthe film of the official cere\nmonies at Glenview Civic Center\non October 13 when Rockville\nand Pinneberg affiliated as part\nof the international program\nsponsored by the United Stales\nInformation Agency. Copies of\n(Continued on Page 41\nSmith is elected president of the\nschool board David Vernon\nIJall, 15, admits bludgeoning\nclassmate Georgette Hentgen in\nSilver Spring because she slapped\nhim School Board cuts build\ning program $3 million Rock\nville annexes Burgundy Knolls,\nEstates and the Fruit farm in\ncreasing size of county seat by 15\npercent.\nFebruary\nDamascus completes new water\nutilities tank Winship I. Green\nsucceeds father as president of\nthe Fanners Banking and Trust\nCo. Peoples Drug opens Twin\n(Continued on Page 5)\nTwinbrook Liquor\nOutlet is Killed\nCounty Gains in Fight\nTo Buy Liquor Direct\nThe county liquor dispen\nsary system apparently has\nwon its fight to keep liquor\nprices down\u2014and competitive\nwith the District\u2014by buying\nwhisky directly from the man\nufacturer.\nA United States District Court\nin Baltimore Monday fined the\nMaryland Package Liquor Stores\nAssociation and its president a\ntotal of S7OOO on charges of con\nspiring to fix liquor prices in the\ncounty.\nThe fines came after the de\nfendants entered \u201cno contest\u201d\npleas. Other defendants have\nchosen to take their cases to a\njury Monday.\nGaithersburg Youth Faces\nHousebreaking Charges\nA 21-year-old Quince Orchards\nyouth released on SIOOO bond for\ngrand jury action on a charge of\nbreaking into People\u2019s Court,\nRockville, was arrested the same\nday on another housebreaking\ncharge.\nPolice said Gordon Leon Con\ntee was re-arrested on a larceny\ncharge December 23 after break\ning into the Citizens\u2019 Building and\nLoan Association, 12 S. Perry\nStreet, Rockville.\nJudge Einor B. Christensen in\nRockville People\u2019s Court Monday\nordered Contee held for the grand\njury without bond. The next reg\nular session of the grand jury will\nconvene in March.\nContee now faces five charges\nincluding housebreaking at the\ncourthouse on November 11, two l\nGermantown\nMan Hit by\nAuto Dies\nRichard Lowe, 34, of RFD 1,\nGermantown, died Saturday at 1\nP.M. at Suburban Hospital after\nbeing struck by a car while cross\ning old Rout 4 240 near Gaithers\nburg last Thursday.\nMontgomery County police said\nAubrey Albert Clagett, 38, also!\nof RFD 1, Germantown, driver of\nthe car, reported he could not stop I\nin time when he saw Lowe walk- j\ning across the highway about 600\nfeet south of Germantown Road.\nA native of Germantown, Mr.\nLowe was married with three j\nsons. Funeral services were held;\nat 11 A.M. Tuesday from the!\nGardner Funeral Home in Gaith-I\nersburg. Burial was in Forest\nOak Cemetery.\nBesides his wife, Mrs. Louise,\nLowe, and sons, he leaves his\nmother, Mrs. Nellie Lowe; six\nbrothers, Lawrence, John,\nCharles, Glen, Harry and Herbert;\nand two sisters, Mary and Joyce,\nall of Germantown.\nBurns Gets 30\nDays in Jail\nJames Edward Burns. Burtons\nville, was sentenced by Judge j\nSamuel Gordon in Silver Spring j\nPeople\u2019s Court Monday to 30\ndays in jail for possession of a\nconcealed weapon Dec. 27 at the:\nFalrland Lunch room In Burtons-;\nville.\nPolice reported Burns had u\n.22 caliber German-made revolver\nin a hip pocket and also charged\nhim with drunkenness. Judge\nGordon, Imposing a $lO fine or\nfive days In Jail on the drunk\ncharge, admonished the defend-;\nant that it was bad enough to\nbe drunk but an intoxicated per\nl son had no business carrying j\nweapons.\nSimilar charges were filed\nagainst 51 other defendants. Ten\ndays ago 17 of them also entered\n\u201cno contest\u201d pleas and were fined\na total of $57,000 by Judge Roszel\nC. Thomsen. Thirty-four cases re\nmain to be settled.\nThe court action evolved from\na fight begun by the county three\nyears ago when certain whisky\nmanufacturers refused to sell to\ncounty liquor dispensaries.\nThe county for many years has\nbought its whisky from the manu\nfacturers in an effort to compete\nwith the lower prices in Wash\nington liquor stores. The manu\nfacturers, on the other hand,\nclaimed that retailers were being\nhurt by losing sales.\nincidents of theft from offices in\nthe County Office Building De\ncember 17 and 18, housebreaking\nand larceny at the Citizens' Build\ning and Loan December 23.\nAccording to police, Contee\nstole a wallet containing S4O and\ntoo two-cent stamps and identifi\ncation cards belonging to Char\nmain Elken from Room 359 of\nthe County Office building, and\nsl4 from the health department\noffice of Margaret Burch in the\nCounty Office building.\nOn December 23, police report\ned, Contee broke into the office\nof Claude R. Vess at the Citizens\u2019\nbuilding and is charged with\nlarceny of $230 from that office.\nContee has been called before\nJuvenile Court \u201cseveral times,\u201d\nan official said.\nWhittier\nBudgetTo\nBe Aired\n\"Standing Room Only\u201d is\nexpected tomorrow night at\nthe County Building auditori\num at 8 P.M. when the public\nwill express its vietvs on Su\nperintendent C. Taylor Whit\ntier\u2019s $13.8 million school con\nstruction budget for 1958-\u201959.\nThis Is a million dollars higher\nthan the superintendent\u2019s request\nlast year and a $5 million in\ncrease over the actual appropria\ntion granted by the codnty\ncouncil.\nThe largest share of the con\nstruction money will go for three\nnew secondary schools to meet\nthe increase in Junior-senior high\nenrollment expected by 1960.\nTwo senior highs, Aspen and\nSpringbrook, and a Junior high\nin West Rockville have been re\nquested by the superintendent\nfor a total of $7.2 million.\nHowever, four of the seven\nschool board members have al\nready indicated that they favor\nconverting Carver Senior High\ninto an integrated junior high\nas a substitute that would save\nclose to a million dollars over a\nnew building In Rockville\u2019s west\nend.\nSix new elementary schools\nand additions and modifications to\n16 olementaries and seven sec\nondary schools are also included.\nWhittier is asking for a new\nscience building for the Junior\nCollege and planning and site\nmoney for a new administration\nbuilding to be constructed around\n1960.\nMost School News\nThe Sentinel regularly car\nries more than twice as mncta\nMontgomery County school\nnews as any other daily or\nweekly newspaper. Keep up\nwith school news all year long\nwith the Sentinel.\nCounty Heads\nVote Step by\nTally of 4-3\nGingery Role\nIn Lease Cited\nAs a Factor\nBy Marge Flynn\nStaff Krportrr\nEstablishment of a county\nliquor dispensary in the Twin\nbrook Shopping Center was\ndefeated 4-3 Tuesday by the\nCounty Council.\nVoting against County Manager\nMelvin L. Reese\u2019s recommenda\ntion that the cqunty lease prop\nerty owned by Joseph Geeraert at\n$2.65 a square foot were Coun\ncllwoman Stella B. Werner, Coun\ncilmen Charles Jamison, Jerry\nWilliams and Grover Walker.\nThose in favor were Councilmen\nWilbur Baughman, J. Grahame\nWalker and Robert Snure.\nThe county manager told the\ncouncil that half of a 39-foot-wide\nstore could be leased at $2.65 a\nsquare foot without air-condition\ning. or at $2.90 a square foot with\nair-conditioning. The manager\nrecommended rental of the site at\nthe lower price with the county\nproviding its own air-conditioning\nsystem.\nMrs. Werner objected to a \"dis\npensary in every new little shop\nping center,\" pointing out there\nwere dispensaries In Vlers Mill\nshopping area and in Bockville.\nShe maintained the intent of the\ndispensary system was for con\ntrol, not expansion by the county.\nJ. Grahame Walker replied that\n\"it is not fair to say we're going\nto put one in every little shopping\ncenter.\u201d He contended the Intent\nwas not to withhold but to pro\ni vide liquor outlets under a con\ntrolled system.\nWilliams expressed the opinion\nthat there are enough dispen\nsaries in the county now.\nGrover Walker asked if the\ncounty could lease property\nowned across the road by Donald\nGingery and offered at a rental\nrate of $2.45 per square foot with\nout air-conditioning.\nCounty Attorney Charles Ire\nlan advised that provisions of the\ncounty charter restricting trans\nactions among persons receiving\ncounty pay \"do not tie the coun\ni oil's hand in acquiring real prop\nerty.\"\nDonald Gingery is a member\nof the Maryland-National Capital\nPark and Planning Commission\nand Montgomery County Plan\nning Board.\nGrover Walker who had made\na motion that the county lease\nj the Gingery property at $2.45 a\nsquare foot, after the lease of the\nGeeraert property had been de\nfeated, withdrew his motion.\nJ. Grahame Walker pointed out\ni that such an action might bring\ncriticism on the county govern\nment- and also that the county\nmanager had recommended the\nGeeraert property as the better\nlocation for people to stop and\nshop on their way home from\nI downtown. \"It would be a mis\ntake to fly in the face of these\ntwo factors,\u201d Walker said.\nSnure also pointed out that\nlocation of a county dispensary\nmust in? on the recommendation\nof the county manager.\nResidents of Twinbrook voted\n3 to 1 in favor of a county-oper\nated liquor dispensary in a com\nmunity poll about six weeks ago.\nWorth\u2019s Lists\n\u2018Well\u2019 Winners\nWinners this week in Worth's\ndepartment store \"Wishing Well\u201d\ncontest were Milton T. Lawrey, of\n.301 Cedar Lane, Rockville, and\nMrs. q. A. McLellan, Jr., of 1204\nEdmonston Drive, Rockville.\nLawrey won a $65 Botany suit\nand Mrs. McLellan won a S6O\nHandmacher suit.","height":"27329","width":"21596"}}
